This piece and it’s process was a little more remarkable for me, a chunk of tree that came down in a storm a few years ago, that I had originally carved a face into as a shop mascot while he dried out and watched me through many pieces, trials, life. One of the most important and least talked about parts of the creative process is doing things the absolute dumbest way because you want to do it NOW, RIGHT NOW.  You are able to convince yourself (usually around 1am) it is more expedient to do it the wrong way and make more work for yourself, then to wait until you have the correct materials and tools and start later. These impractical thoughts are usually powered by one idea you had 4 minutes ago. I would say don’t be that artist, but…always be that artist. 🤪 #doyou #dobad #dosomething

Taking a bit of a new direction, truer to my heart. I love making serving pieces and will be continuing, don’t worry. But creating art for arts sake is my passion, pieces to hang in your space that draw you in, make you want to touch them, play with texture in new ways. You’ll be seeing a lot more of that here. This piece is inspired by the beautiful craftsmanship of pieced #leather, usually found in the practical pieces we carry every day, and don’t spend much time looking at or truly appreciating. This was a labor of love, handcarved in Black Limba wood, recreating the technical aspects of how another material moves and puckers, and giving it permanence, like a photograph you can touch. This piece is 17x17, with a keyhole back for hanging. $1350, shipped. Comment or DM to purchase. #handcarved #woodwork #girlswhowoodwork #sculpture

💔 This has been the hardest 16 days of my life. On October 1st, I lost my best friend. I don’t share much or really any of my private life on this account, but honoring his life HERE in particular is so important to me, because I would not be anything you see without him. Ten years ago, he came into my life at 7.5 weeks old, and every choice I’ve made since then has revolved around being where he is, which led me to a life of making. Every single thing I’ve made, he watched. Every day in the shop, he was there. Every struggle, he witnessed. Illnesses, we did those. Every win, he celebrated with me. He was everywhere, all the time, always. I have not yet figured out life with this hole in my heart and this empty bed by my bench. I poured my grief energy into carving him an urn, because after watching me make everything I’ve made, he wasn’t going to rest eternally in a box from a catalog. And now that he’s back home, I walk into the shop, and I don’t know what to do. There is a 185lb absence, which is just SO BIG. Forgive my lack of posts for now. I want to keep making. I know I will keep making, for him. Soon. 🖤🐾 #petloss #petgrief

If you’ve been following me for a minute, you probably noticed I fell off the planet after my best friend died. My best friend was a giant Great Dane, who has spent every minute in the shop with me since this journey began. He took up some space. A gigantic ball of dog at my feet, in a gigantic bed that I would trip over constantly. happily. When you are an artist, and taking up one space for hours on end, at ALL hours, having someone with you for all of them to talk to, to stretch with, to take breaks with, to look at and *😀* when a great song comes on, is the difference between feeling normal and feeling isolated. When he left, I went out there and I made him the most amazing urn that he deserved, and then I closed the door and didn’t go back. And I didn’t want to. I applied for any job I saw locally. No one called. I sat in front of a huge box of yarn in my kitchen and thought maybe I take a hard 180 and make yarn things now. Anything to not go back out to the shop. And then I realized my misery in missing him was that he’s not at some retail store job, he’s not happy watching me make little bits and bobs of yarn ornaments in front of a TV in the kitchen, he’s with me outside, loving me while I’m loving what I do, and what I’m great at. He built this with me. His energy was part of what made me happy doing this, and it’s still there. It’s hard to understand I think, if you’re a person who has a regular job around people that fill your day. Or if you are a “it’s just a dog” person. I was part of a little team. And now I go forward solo. That said. Books are reopened.  Keep me busy. 🖤

The many, many, fruits of my time out of the shop. That said, if you are in the market for some very bohemian floral Pom Pom baubles, this is the tip of the iceberg, and I’m your girl. Grief is a wild ride, some days you will do anything to make a day feel totally unfamiliar so you don’t notice what’s missing as much.  Im back in the shop now, but this is a relaxing little hobby I will probably hang on to. #hygge #hyggehome
